Connecting Virtual Networks is essential for building scalable and distributed architectures.

For example, a global company may connect VNets across regions using VNet peering.

A real-life use case is separating production and development environments into different VNets while allowing controlled communication.

Another example is connecting VNets across departments for shared services like authentication or logging.

Organizations also use hub-and-spoke architecture, where a central VNet provides shared services to multiple VNets.

This approach improves scalability, security, and resource sharing.
